Problem 1a - Time Plot of Spot Crude Oil Prices

Beginning in 2004, crude oil prices have experienced a steady upward trend. Seasonality reveals the increases and decreases throughout the calendar year. Typically during the summer oil prices rise as demand increases due to traveling, and will return to lower prices toward the end of the year. During the tumultuous financial crisis between 2007-2010, there was a significant rise and fall of oil price, ultimately reaching a peak in 2008 and fall to its lowest price in 2009. Prices continued on an upward trend after 2009, experiencing greater volatility between 2010 and 2014 until another extreme drop in price in 2015.

Problem 1b - Percentage Change of Spot Crude Oil Prices

Percent change rates remained relatively steady in terms of volatility from 2004 up until 2008, when there were larger swings in the percent change rate, reaching its largest swing in 2009. Prices during this time changed drastically month by month. Volatility returned to normal swings in 2010, and even experienced more steady pricing from 2013 to the end of 2015, when fluctuations began to increase.

Problem 1c - Histogram of Percent Change Rate

The distribution of percent change rates is slightly skewed to the right. What this translates to is that between 2004 and 2016, we saw a greater distribution of positive percent change rates than we did negative percent change rates. This distribution is almost close to a normal distribution however, as there are only a few more distribution ranges that are positive than there are negative.
